<script id="tpl-msrl" type="text/x-template">
<div class="det-hero">
  <div class="back-link" onclick="showPage('projects')">Back to Projects</div>
  <div class="det-badge">RAA S2 2025</div>
  <h1 class="det-title">Conceptual Design for a Multi-Stage Mars Lander and Sample Return Mission</h1>
  <p class="det-sub">Rice C-ARK — a 5-stage system to reach Mars, collect geological samples, and return them to Earth.</p>
  <div class="meta-row">
    <div class="mi"><span class="ml">Program</span><span class="mv">Rice Aerospace Academy</span></div>
    <div class="mi"><span class="ml">Date</span><span class="mv">July 2025</span></div>
    <div class="mi"><span class="ml">Tools</span><span class="mv">Onshape · GrabCAD · NASA Data</span></div>
    <div class="mi"><span class="ml">Team</span><span class="mv">5 Members</span></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="dbody">
  <h2 data-n="00">Abstract</h2>
  <div class="callout"><p>A conceptual design for the Mars Sample Recovery Lander (MSRL-A), purpose-built to collect volcanic dust, rock, and ice from the Martian surface and return them to Earth — the first mission architecture designed with full return functionality.</p></div>
  <p>Inspired by NASA's Perseverance, Ingenuity, and InSight missions, this system uses a 5-stage launch architecture. A companion drone unit, MSRL-B, conducts on-surface sample collection over a multi-month operational phase. Budget, mission length, and material constraints were factored through multiple rounds of collaborative design iteration.</p>

  <h2 data-n="01">Introduction &amp; Background</h2>
  <p>Previous Mars missions — Perseverance, Ingenuity, InSight, Curiosity — were all successful, but none were designed to <strong>return</strong>. This project addresses that gap directly. Bringing physical Martian samples back to Earth enables detailed geological analysis and could reveal evidence of past or present microbial life in Martian permafrost ice.</p>
  <p>Strong indicators that Mars once had enough surface water to support life make a sample return mission both scientifically critical and socially compelling.</p>

  <h2 data-n="02">Mission Timeline</h2>
  <div class="tline">
    <div class="titem"><div class="tphase">Phase 1 — Earth Launch</div><div class="ttext">5-stage rocket launches. Stage 5 propels the stack out of Earth's atmosphere, detaches, and returns for reuse. Stage 4 ion propulsion activates for Mars transit.</div></div>
    <div class="titem"><div class="tphase">Phase 2 — Mars Orbital Insertion</div><div class="ttext">Stages 1–3 (lander) detach from Stage 4. Stage 4 remains in Martian orbit as communications satellite and energy hub for the return journey.</div></div>
    <div class="titem"><div class="tphase">Phase 3 — Entry, Descent &amp; Landing</div><div class="ttext">Heat shield protects during entry. Parachute deploys from Stage 1 top. Retro-thrusters on Stage 3 control final descent. Drills anchor the lander to the surface.</div></div>
    <div class="titem"><div class="tphase">Phase 4 — Surface Operations (4–6 months)</div><div class="ttext">After system checks, MSRL-B drone deploys to collect volcanic dust, rock, and ice — depositing samples into secured pods within the lander.</div></div>
    <div class="titem"><div class="tphase">Phase 5 — Mars Ascent &amp; Rendezvous</div><div class="ttext">MSRL-A launches. Stage 3 detaches, Stage 2 takes over. Stage 1 uses ion propulsion to dock with Stage 4 in orbit.</div></div>
    <div class="titem"><div class="tphase">Phase 6 — Earth Return</div><div class="ttext">Stage 1 + Stage 4 transit back to Earth. An EVA mission recovers the Martian samples in Earth orbit.</div></div>
  </div>

  <h2 data-n="03">5-Stage Architecture</h2>
  <div class="scard"><div class="sbadge">S1</div><div><div class="stitle">Lander Core + Drone Housing</div><div class="sdesc">Houses MSRL-B drone and sample pods. Ion propulsion for post-ascent orbital re-alignment. Re-attachment hatch for Stage 4 docking. This is the stage that returns to Earth with samples.</div></div></div>
  <div class="scard"><div class="sbadge">S2</div><div><div class="stitle">Mars Ascent Engine Stage</div><div class="sdesc">Raptor 3 liquid-fuel engines provide Mars ascent thrust. Deployable solar panels activate at designated mission phases.</div></div></div>
  <div class="scard"><div class="sbadge">S3</div><div><div class="stitle">Descent, Landing &amp; Initial Ascent Stage</div><div class="sdesc">Manages EDL — heat shield, retro-thrusters, landing gear. Uses remaining fuel for initial ascent burn, then detaches.</div></div></div>
  <div class="scard"><div class="sbadge">S4</div><div><div class="stitle">Orbital Relay &amp; Return Platform</div><div class="sdesc">Ion propulsion for Earth↔Mars transit. Remains in Martian orbit as communications hub. Docks with Stage 1 for the return journey.</div></div></div>
  <div class="scard"><div class="sbadge">S5</div><div><div class="stitle">Earth Launch Vehicle (Reusable Booster)</div><div class="sdesc">Raptor 3 cluster launches Stages 1–4 from Earth. Designed for recovery and reuse — modeled on SpaceX Super Heavy booster architecture.</div></div></div>

  <h2 data-n="04">Design Iteration &amp; Budget Analysis</h2>
  <p>The team cycled through multiple design iterations, with each major revision going through structured team discussion. When lift-to-weight ratio challenges arose for Martian ascent, stage architecture was revised against Martian escape velocity data and NASA Mars Fact Sheet parameters — surface gravity 3.72 m/s², atmospheric pressure ~1% of Earth's.</p>
  <p>Budget feasibility was analyzed against current mission cost benchmarks. Material choices — perovskite solar panels over conventional silicon, Raptor 3 engines for dual-use efficiency — were selected to balance cost and performance. Mission duration was estimated at 18–24 months total, with the 4–6 month surface phase driving the majority of operational cost.</p>

  <h2 data-n="05">MSRL-B Drone Comparison</h2>
  <table class="spec-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Ingenuity (NASA)</th><th>MSRL-B (This Mission)</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Surface Area</td><td>~0.14 m²</td><td>~3–4 m² (foldable)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Power Source</td><td>Solar + Li-Ion</td><td>Perovskite Solar</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Operational Life</td><td>~30 days planned</td><td>4–6 months (years possible)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Primary Purpose</td><td>Aerial reconnaissance</td><td>Sample collection &amp; deposit</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Leg Design</td><td>Fixed</td><td>Foldable for transport</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 data-n="06">Conclusion</h2>
  <div class="callout"><p>"The use of modern materials and propulsion would allow this concept to meet its objectives within a reasonable margin of current technology."</p></div>
  <p>The architecture could scale into a full Mars Infrastructure System — a network of landers, drones, and orbital platforms enabling continuous unmanned operations before any crewed mission reaches the surface.</p>

  <div class="refs">
    <h3>Works Cited</h3>
    <div class="ref">NASA. "Ingenuity Mars Helicopter." NASA Science. science.nasa.gov</div>
    <div class="ref">NASA. "Mars Fact Sheet." NSSDCA, May 2025. nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov</div>
    <div class="ref">NASA. "Mars InSight Lander." NASA Science. science.nasa.gov</div>
