  <h1 class="det-title">POE Prosthetic Hand</h1>
  <p class="det-sub">A fully modeled and 3D-printed prosthetic device with articulating fingers — engineered from scratch for smooth movement and reliable grip strength.</p>
  <div class="meta-row">
    <div class="mi"><span class="ml">Course</span><span class="mv">Principles of Engineering (POE)</span></div>
    <div class="mi"><span class="ml">Tools</span><span class="mv">CAD Software · 3D Printer</span></div>
    <div class="mi"><span class="ml">Domain</span><span class="mv">Biomedical Engineering</span></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="dbody">
  <h2 data-n="01">Project Overview</h2>
  <p>In my Principles of Engineering course, I designed and fabricated a <strong>functional prosthetic hand</strong> from scratch — taking the project through the full engineering design cycle: research, concept sketching, CAD modeling, iterative refinement, and physical 3D printing.</p>
  <div class="callout"><p>The goal wasn't just a hand that looks like a hand — it needed to work like one. Smooth articulation across all fingers, and grip strength sufficient to hold and retain objects securely.</p></div>

  <h2 data-n="02">Design Process</h2>
  <p>The design began by studying existing prosthetic hand architectures to understand the mechanical constraints of finger articulation. Key design challenges included:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Achieving full finger flexion and extension through a printable joint mechanism</li>
    <li>Balancing structural rigidity with the flexibility needed for realistic movement</li>
    <li>Selecting print orientation and material to maximize tensile strength at joint interfaces</li>
    <li>Minimizing part count while maintaining full mechanical functionality</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Multiple CAD iterations were created and evaluated before arriving at the final print-ready model. The finger joints were engineered as a tendon-actuated system, mimicking the mechanical logic of a real human hand.</p>

  <h2 data-n="03">Fabrication &amp; Results</h2>
  <p>The final model was 3D printed and assembled. The prosthetic achieved its core performance targets: <strong>smooth movement</strong> across all digits and a <strong>firm grip</strong> capable of securely holding objects.</p>
  <p>This project deepened my understanding of how engineering constraints — print tolerances, material properties, joint geometry — interact in physical fabrication, and how small CAD decisions translate directly into real-world function or failure.</p>

  <h2 data-n="04">Reflection</h2>
  <p>The POE hand was my first complete end-to-end engineering project: from blank screen in CAD to a physical, functioning device. It established the discipline I bring to every project since — design with the final physical object in mind from the very first sketch.</p>

  <div class="det-footer" style="justify-content:flex-end">
    <a class="btn btn-outline" href="#" onclick="showPage('projects');return false;">← All Projects</a>
  </div>
</div>
</script>

<script id="tpl-rocket" type="text/x-template">
