</div>
<div class="dbody">
  <h2 data-n="01">Project Overview</h2>
  <p>This lab at Rice Aerospace Academy introduced a critical real-world engineering dimension that student projects often ignore: <strong>economic constraints</strong>. Students were given a simulated budget and an economic system to acquire materials — every component had a cost, and every design decision had a financial consequence.</p>
  <div class="callout"><p>Build an aircraft that performs as well as possible within a fixed budget. Spend too much on materials and you run out. Skimp on structure and it fails on launch.</p></div>

  <h2 data-n="02">Budget System &amp; Documentation</h2>
  <p>The economic system required teams to document all expenditures, calculate running totals, and remain within their allocated budget throughout the build. This meant:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Trade-off analysis between higher-performance and lower-cost materials</li>
    <li>Prioritization decisions — which components justify higher spend</li>
    <li>Real-time budget tracking and documentation throughout the lab</li>
    <li>Redesigning sections mid-build when original material choices exceeded budget</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 data-n="03">Design &amp; Construction</h2>
  <p>The water pressure rocket was designed for maximum altitude and stability. Key engineering considerations included fin geometry for directional stability, nose cone aerodynamics, and pressure vessel integrity for the water propulsion chamber. All design choices were filtered through the budget constraint — creating an authentic engineering trade-off environment that mirrors real aerospace procurement challenges.</p>

  <h2 data-n="04">Outcome &amp; Lessons</h2>
  <p>The lab demonstrated that <strong>engineering is never just a technical problem</strong> — it's always also an economic one. The best-performing rockets were those whose teams made the best decisions under constraint. That lesson shapes how I approach every project I take on.</p>

  <div class="det-footer" style="justify-content:flex-end">
    <a class="btn btn-outline" href="#" onclick="showPage('projects');return false;">← All Projects</a>
  </div>
</div>
</script>

<script id="tpl-balsa" type="text/x-template">
<div class="det-hero">
  <div class="back-link" onclick="showPage('projects')">Back to Projects</div>
  <div class="det-badge">Aerospace Fabrication</div>
  <h1 class="det-title">Aerospace Balsa Wood Plane</h1>
  <p class="det-sub">Simulation-informed design meets precision hand fabrication — building a flying aircraft from calculated aerodynamic parameters.</p>
  <div class="meta-row">
    <div class="mi"><span class="ml">Tools</span><span class="mv">Plane Maker / Simulator</span></div>
    <div class="mi"><span class="ml">Material</span><span class="mv">Balsa Wood</span></div>
    <div class="mi"><span class="ml">Focus</span><span class="mv">Aerodynamics · Precision Fabrication</span></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="dbody">
  <h2 data-n="01">Project Overview</h2>
  <p>This project combined computational simulation with physical fabrication: use <strong>plane-maker software</strong> to calculate the ideal scale, wing shape, and weight distribution for a flying aircraft — then build it by hand from balsa wood to those exact specifications.</p>
  <div class="callout"><p>The simulation isn't just a planning tool — it's the engineering blueprint. Every measurement cut into the balsa wood is a direct output of the aerodynamic model.</p></div>

  <h2 data-n="02">Simulation &amp; Parameter Calculation</h2>
  <p>Using the plane-maker simulator, I analyzed key aerodynamic variables governing flight performance:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Wing aspect ratio</strong> — optimizing lift-to-drag for glide performance</li>
    <li><strong>Center of gravity vs. center of lift</strong> — ensuring a stable flight envelope</li>
    <li><strong>Fuselage length and mass distribution</strong> — balancing pitch stability</li>
    <li><strong>Control surface sizing</strong> — calculating effective elevator and rudder areas</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Simulation output defined the exact dimensions — span, chord, fuselage length, and component weights — that the physical build had to match.</p>

  <h2 data-n="03">Fabrication</h2>
  <p>Balsa wood was cut, shaped, and assembled to the simulation-derived measurements. Precision was critical — small deviations in wing geometry or weight distribution shift the center of gravity and degrade flight stability. The build demanded both fine cutting technique and continuous weight verification throughout assembly.</p>

  <h2 data-n="04">Outcome</h2>
  <p>The completed aircraft matched the simulation parameters and demonstrated the core lesson: <strong>simulation is only as good as the build it informs</strong>. Executing the physical artifact to spec — with real materials and real tolerances — is its own engineering discipline entirely.</p>

  <div class="det-footer" style="justify-content:flex-end">
    <a class="btn btn-outline" href="#" onclick="showPage('projects');return false;">← All Projects</a>
  </div>
</div>
</script>

