  <h2 data-n="03">Collaboration &amp; Cultural Exchange</h2>
  <p>Working with students from 10+ countries meant that the design process itself was a lesson in cross-cultural engineering communication. Each group brought different assumptions about what a city needs, different aesthetic sensibilities, and different definitions of "sustainable." Navigating those differences — while representing Honduras's specific needs — was as challenging and rewarding as the technical design work.</p>
  <p>The camp reinforced that the most important engineering problems — energy, water, urban mobility, climate resilience — are <strong>global problems that demand global thinking</strong>.</p>

  <h2 data-n="04">Outcome &amp; Significance</h2>
  <p>The completed model presented a cohesive vision for a sustainable Honduran city, grounded in the country's real constraints and opportunities. For me personally, the project reinforced that engineering is most meaningful when it's applied to the places and communities you care about. Honduras shaped who I am as an engineer. This project let me give something back.</p>

